MEDIUM|internal/payload/diff.go:223|When every changed file in the range matches .gitignore/.atcrignore (e.g. a PR that only bumps a lockfile or touches vendored code), applyIgnore returns an empty kept slice. ApplyByteBudget([]) does not trip AllDropped, so PrepareReview fails with the misleading error 'the range contains commits but no changed files (only merge or empty commits?)' — a false hypothesis that gives no hint that --no-ignore would surface the filtered files.|Distinguish 'nothing changed' from 'everything was ignore-filtered'. Have applyIgnore/changedFilesMemo signal that files existed pre-filter and emit a dedicated diagnostic like 'all N changed files were excluded by .gitignore/.atcrignore; re-run with --no-ignore to review them'. Verify with a fixture whose entire changed set matches an ignore rule.|error-handling|60|internal/payload/diff.go:223-248, internal/fanout/review.go:250-260|claude
MEDIUM|cmd/atcr/resume.go:104|runReview passes --no-ignore through to the fresh path, but runResume builds its ReviewRequest (lines 104-116) without setting NoIgnore, so it defaults false, and NoIgnore is not persisted in the manifest. PrepareResume calls buildPayloads(..., req.NoIgnore) with that hardcoded false. If the original run used --no-ignore and an ignored file changed in the range, completed agents reviewed the file (unfiltered) but resumed pending agents get it filtered out — a silent inconsistent-context divergence that base/head-SHA resume validation cannot catch. Passing --no-ignore again on resume does not help: runResume never reads the flag.|Persist NoIgnore in payload.Manifest on the fresh run and recover it in PrepareResume from the manifest — mirroring how SprintPlanPath/scope is locked to on-disk state (resume.go:288-296 comment). Reading the flag into the resume req alone is wrong per the resume-locking philosophy; the value must come from the original run.|correctness|60|cmd/atcr/resume.go:104-116, internal/fanout/resume.go:283, internal/payload/manifest.go:16-27|claude
MEDIUM|internal/fanout/review.go:244|Existing coverage is TestReviewCmd_NoIgnoreFlagRegistered (flag exists, defaults false) and TestRangeBuilder_NoIgnoreOption_IncludesIgnored (payload primitive). Neither exercises the wiring between: no test asserts PrepareReview with req.NoIgnore=true yields unfiltered payloads, and nothing asserts the resume path preserves it — which is why the resume regression is invisible behind a green suite.|Add a fanout-level test that runs PrepareReview (and PrepareResume) against a range containing an ignored, changed file, asserting the ignored file is present in the built payload when NoIgnore=true and absent when false. The resume case should assert the value survives an interrupt/resume cycle.|testing|60|internal/fanout/review.go:241-247, internal/fanout/resume.go:283, cmd/atcr/review_test.go:304-312|claude
LOW|internal/payload/diff.go:75|changedFiles/headPathSet run 'git diff --name-status -M' with no pathspec (whole repo), but diffChunks/binarySet append pathspecArgs = '-- . :(exclude,literal)...' whose positive '.' is relative to g.dir (== Repo, hardcoded '.' = CWD, not pinned to repo root). Run from a repo subdirectory with an active ignore file, a changed file above the subdir stays in headPathSet but its chunk is dropped from the '.'-scoped diff; the splitter tolerates the missing chunk, so that file gets a silently empty body. Invisible at repo root where '.' == everything.|Resolve g.dir to the repo toplevel (git rev-parse --show-toplevel) before loading the matcher and building pathspecs, or scope changedFiles' --name-status with the same '.' so both sides agree. Verify by running a review from a subdirectory with an active .gitignore and a changed file above the subdir.|correctness|60|internal/payload/diff.go:68-76, 164-165, 250-262, 392-408|claude
LOW|internal/payload/diff.go:243|changedFiles maps both 'R' and 'C' status to kindRenamed. applyIgnore, for any kindRenamed whose head path is ignored, also emits :(exclude,literal)<oldPath>. For a true rename the source is gone (safe), but for a COPY the source survives and may be an independently modified file with its own kept entry — excluding its path drops that file's diff chunk, leaving an empty body with no error. Currently unreachable: -M alone never emits 'C' (only -C does), so the 'C' handling is dead defensive code today, but becomes silent data loss the moment copy detection is enabled.|Only exclude oldPath for genuine renames, not copies — track copy vs rename distinctly instead of collapsing both into kindRenamed, or drop the 'C' branch in changedFiles given -M never produces it. Verify with a -C diff where the copy target is ignored and its source is separately modified.|correctness|30|internal/payload/diff.go:183-187, 241-245|claude
LOW|internal/payload/grounding.go:37|The package-level BuildChangedLines (and package BuildEntries/BuildDiff) construct a bare gitRunner{} with noIgnore defaulting false and no option to disable filtering, unlike RangeBuilder. The review flow grounds via rb.BuildChangedLines (honors --no-ignore); the standalone call at fanout/review.go:448 is a documented never-taken-for-git-range fallback. If reached under --no-ignore, grounding filters out ignored files while the payload kept them, so every finding on an ignored file is silently dropped by the grounding gate (file absent from changed-lines map).|Give the standalone entry points a filtering toggle (or route the fallback through a runner that inherits req.NoIgnore) so grounding and payload always agree. Verify a --no-ignore review whose grounding takes the standalone path keeps findings on ignored files.|maintainability|30|internal/payload/grounding.go:36-42, internal/fanout/review.go:444-449|claude
LOW|internal/payload/builder.go:136|The Epic 26.0 comment asserts ChangedFileCount 'reflects the SAME ignore-filtered set BuildEntries produces ... the two must agree'. But ChangedFileCount (builder.go:141) hardcodes gitRunner{} with noIgnore=false and has no param to disable filtering, while a --no-ignore review's BuildEntries runs unfiltered — so under --no-ignore they disagree (count smaller than reviewed set), the opposite of what the comment describes. Unreachable today (only caller is the MCP handler, which never sets NoIgnore) but the stated invariant is false the moment any --no-ignore path calls it; same gap applies to package-level BuildEntries.|Give ChangedFileCount/package BuildEntries a noIgnore parameter (or option) for symmetry with NewRangeBuilder, or narrow the comment to state the invariant holds only for filtered (default) runs and note the --no-ignore divergence explicitly.|maintainability|30|internal/payload/builder.go:133-150, 96-101|claude
